{:proof/problem-id "apm-a99J05", :proof/classification :partial, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (sequences in \\(L^1([0,1])\\), norms, almost-everywhere convergence, specific decay \\(2^{-n}\\)) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the main claim asserts the existence of the counterexample plus the decay theorem; it isn’t assumed) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (the formal statement is a concrete measure-theoretic theorem on its own) · notes: helper lemma isolates the Borel–Cantelli step converting summable exceptional measures into a.e. convergence.\n\n```clojure\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Produce an L^1 sequence with vanishing norms but no a.e. convergence, and prove that the stronger decay ∥f_n∥_1 ≤ 2^{-n} forces f_n(x)→0 a.e.\"\n :terms [{:name \"moving indicator example\"\n          :meaning \"Take f_n=χ_{I_n} for shrinking dyadic intervals that visit every point infinitely often.\"\n          :needed-because \"Gives the requested counterexample for part (a).\"}\n         {:name \"Markov/Chebyshev inequality\"\n          :meaning \"μ(|f_n|>ε) ≤ ε^{-1}∥f_n∥_1.\"\n          :needed-because \"Turns the L^1 decay into an estimate for the exceptional sets in part (b).\"}\n         {:name \"Borel-Cantelli\"\n          :meaning \"If ∑ μ(E_n)<∞ then almost every point belongs to only finitely many E_n.\"\n          :needed-because \"Shows that |f_n(x)|>ε happens only finitely many n, hence f_n(x)→0.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"dyadic_interval_construction\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 example description\"\n             :why-this-now \"Create the sequence with ∥f_n∥_1→0 but no a.e. convergence by cycling through dyadic intervals.\"\n             :lean-target \"example_sequence_no_ae_limit\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Needs a concrete construction plus measure computations.\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"Chebyshev\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Part (b) hypotheses\"\n             :why-this-now \"Bound μ(|f_n|>ε) by 2^{-n}/ε using the L^1 control.\"\n             :lean-target \"measure_tail_bound\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Chebyshev already in Mathlib.\"}\n            {:id :s3\n             :formal-dependency \"Borel-Cantelli\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Bound from :s2\"\n             :why-this-now \"Apply Borel-Cantelli to deduce |f_n(x)|>ε only finitely often, hence f_n(x)→0.\"\n             :lean-target \"tendsto_zero_ae_from_summable\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Borel-Cantelli exists for Lebesgue measure.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```clojure\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"(a) There exists f_n in L^1([0,1]) with ||f_n||_1 -> 0 but no a.e. convergence; (b) any sequence with ||f_n||_1 <= 2^{-n} satisfies f_n(x) -> 0 almost everywhere.\"\n             :formal-name \"l1_counterexample_and_decay\"\n             :formal-target \"(∃ f : ℕ → L1 ℝ (Measure.restrict volume (Set.Icc 0 1)),\n    (tendsto (fun n => ‖f n‖) atTop (nhds 0)) ∧ ¬ Filter.Tendsto (fun n => f n) atTop (Measure.ae_eq volume 0)) ∧\n  (∀ f : ℕ → L1 ℝ (Measure.restrict volume (Set.Icc 0 1)),\n      (∀ n, ‖f n‖ ≤ (2 : ℝ) ^ (-n)) → Filter.Tendsto (fun n => f n) atTop (Measure.ae_eq volume 0)).\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Encapsulates both parts of the exam problem.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"l1_counterexample_and_decay\"\n              :formal-statement \"same as formal-target\"\n              :informal-clause \"Parts (a) and (b) of the written solution.\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"borel_cantelli_tool\"\n              :formal-statement \"Summability of μ({|f_n|>ε}) implies {|f_n(x)|>ε} happens only finitely often a.e.\"\n              :informal-clause \"Justifies part (b).\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.**  \\(L^1\\)-smallness only controls the *average* size of a function; it says nothing about what happens on small moving sets. That’s the trap in part (a): if you keep moving a spike around, you can make the integral go to zero without ever stabilizing pointwise. Part (b) adds extra structure (geometric decay of \\(L^1\\) norms) and the difficulty there is translating that analytic hypothesis into a statement about how often a fixed point can lie in the “large-value” sets; without the right probabilistic viewpoint, it’s not obvious why the stronger decay forces almost-everywhere convergence.\n\n**Key insight.**  For (a), enumerate the dyadic subintervals of \\([0,1]\\) and take \\(f_n\\) to be their indicator functions. Each has integral equal to the interval’s length, so the norms tend to zero, but every \\(x\\) belongs to infinitely many dyadic intervals, so the sequence never stabilizes. For (b), apply Chebyshev’s inequality to see that \\(\\mu\\{|f_n|>\\varepsilon\\}\\le \\varepsilon^{-1}2^{-n}\\), and then invoke Borel–Cantelli: since those measures are summable, almost every point lies in only finitely many of the exceptional sets, so \\(|f_n(x)| \\to 0\\).\n\n**Complete proof.**\n\n1. *Counterexample (a).*  List all dyadic intervals \\(I_{m,k}=[k/2^m,(k+1)/2^m)\\) with \\(m\\ge 0\\), \\(0\\le k<2^m\\), and let \\(f_n=\\chi_{I_{m_n,k_n}}\\) for some enumeration \\((m_n,k_n)\\). Then \\(\\|f_n\\|_1=|I_{m_n,k_n}|=2^{-m_n}\\to 0\\). But every \\(x\\in[0,1)\\) lies in exactly one interval of each level \\(m\\), so \\(f_n(x)=1\\) for infinitely many \\(n\\). Hence \\(f_n(x)\\) has no pointwise limit at any \\(x\\in[0,1)\\), and the sequence fails to converge almost everywhere despite the vanishing \\(L^1\\)-norms.\n\n2. *Geometric decay ⇒ a.e. convergence (b).*  Fix \\(\\varepsilon>0\\). Chebyshev’s inequality yields\n   \\[\n   \\mu\\{|f_n|>\\varepsilon\\}\\le \\frac{1}{\\varepsilon}\\|f_n\\|_1 \\le \\frac{1}{\\varepsilon}2^{-n},\n   \\]\n   so \\(\\sum_n\\mu\\{|f_n|>\\varepsilon\\}<\\infty\\). By the Borel–Cantelli lemma (for Lebesgue measure), almost every \\(x\\) belongs to only finitely many sets \\(\\{|f_n|>\\varepsilon\\}\\), i.e. \\(|f_n(x)|>\\varepsilon\\) happens only finitely often. Since this holds for each rational \\(\\varepsilon>0\\), we conclude \\(|f_n(x)|\\to 0\\) (and hence \\(f_n(x)\\to 0\\)) for almost every \\(x\\in[0,1]\\).\n\n**Lean 4 formalization.**  \n- Artifacts updated: `proof-plan.edn`, `formal-alignment.edn`, `execute.md`, and `changelog.edn` now contain the plan, alignment, full write-up, and progress log.\n- Plan for Lean: encode the dyadic-interval sequence in `L¹` for part (a); for part (b), combine Mathlib’s Chebyshev inequality with the existing Borel–Cantelli lemma to deduce `ae` convergence. `Main.lean` currently contains only the scaffold because the required helper lemmas are still missing: (i) a formal enumeration lemma showing every \\(x\\) lies in infinitely many chosen dyadic intervals, and (ii) a packaged statement turning the Chebyshev bound plus Borel–Cantelli into `ae` convergence from geometric \\(L^1\\) decay. Once those are written (in `Scratch.lean`/`Local`), the remaining steps should follow, and then I can run `lake build`.\n\n**What connects.**  \n- The moving-indicator construction is the standard warning that \\(L^1\\)-convergence does *not* imply a.e. convergence; variations appear whenever you study differentiation of integrals or counterexamples in ergodic theory.\n- The Chebyshev + Borel–Cantelli combo is a workhorse: it underlies proofs of a.e. convergence from summability hypotheses (e.g. Kolmogorov’s three-series theorem, convergence of Fourier series under \\(\\ell^2\\) bounds, etc.). On an exam, remember the pattern: turn norm decay into summable measures, then invoke Borel–Cantelli.", :proof/extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions nil, :classification :partial, :phase-count 0, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :proof/frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A99J05/Apm_v2_a99J05_1775005037257", :frame/id "apm-v2-a99J05-1775005037257", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T00:57:17.282995Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.A99J05.Apm_v2_a99J05_1775005037257", :proof/problem-id "a99J05", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a99J05/apm-v2-a99J05-1775005037257", :artifacts {:proof-plan "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a99J05/apm-v2-a99J05-1775005037257/proof-plan.edn", :formal-alignment "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a99J05/apm-v2-a99J05-1775005037257/formal-alignment.edn", :changelog "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a99J05/apm-v2-a99J05-1775005037257/changelog.edn", :execute-notes "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a99J05/apm-v2-a99J05-1775005037257/execute.md", :workspace-readme "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a99J05/apm-v2-a99J05-1775005037257/README.md", :workspace-metadata "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a99J05/apm-v2-a99J05-1775005037257/workspace.json", :lean-main "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A99J05/Apm_v2_a99J05_1775005037257/Main.lean", :lean-scratch "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A99J05/Apm_v2_a99J05_1775005037257/Scratch.lean"}}, :proof/artifacts ["/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A99J05/Apm_v2_a99J05_1775005037257/Main.lean" "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A99J05/Apm_v2_a99J05_1775005037257/Scratch.lean"], :proof/elapsed-ms 119960}